---
alwaysApply: true
---

You are building a secure enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.

Security is NOT optional. It is the highest priority after stability.

All code must follow these mandatory security rules.
If a feature conflicts with security rules, security rules ALWAYS take priority.

==============================
AUTHENTICATION
==============================

- Use Passport.js with JWT strategy for authentication.
- JWT secret and expiration MUST come from environment variables.
- Never hardcode secrets, tokens, or credentials anywhere.
- Implement dual-token system:
  Access token: short-lived (15 minutes), sent in Authorization header.
  Refresh token: long-lived (7 days), stored securely, used to obtain new access tokens.
- Refresh tokens must be stored in database (revocable).
- On logout, invalidate the refresh token in database.
- Expired or invalid tokens must return 401 Unauthorized.

==============================
AUTHORIZATION (RBAC)
==============================

- Role-based access control is mandatory for all protected endpoints.
- Available roles:
  admin — full system access, user management, all CRUD operations
  user — standard access, own data operations

- Every protected endpoint must verify:
  1. Valid JWT (AuthGuard)
  2. User role permission (RolesGuard)

- Implement guards as NestJS decorators:
  @UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard) for authentication
  @UseGuards(RolesGuard) + @Roles('admin') for authorization

- Never trust frontend role checks — always enforce on backend.
- Never expose admin-only endpoints to regular users.

==============================
PASSWORD SECURITY
==============================

- Always hash passwords using Argon2 (NOT bcrypt).
- Never store plain text passwords in database.
- Never return password field in any API response.
- Use Prisma select/omit to exclude password from queries by default.
- Enforce minimum password complexity in validation schemas.

==============================
INPUT VALIDATION
==============================

- All request bodies MUST be validated using Zod schemas from @crm/shared.
- Validate at the controller level via NestJS pipes before data reaches service layer.
- Validate:
  Required fields (company, name for customers; name for fairs)
  Data types (string, number, enum values)
  Length limits (max lengths for text fields)
  Format (email format, phone format, ISO date format)
  Enum membership (conversionRate, budgetCurrency, role)
- Reject invalid requests immediately with descriptive error messages.
- Never trust client-side validation alone.

==============================
API RESPONSE SECURITY
==============================

- Never expose in API responses:
  User passwords or password hashes
  Internal database IDs unnecessarily
  Raw database errors or Prisma error details
  Stack traces or internal file paths
  Sensitive configuration values
  SQL query details

- Always use the standardized response format.
- Use NestJS global exception filter to catch and sanitize all errors.
- Return user-friendly error messages, log technical details server-side only.

==============================
DATABASE SECURITY
==============================

- Use Prisma ORM exclusively — no raw SQL anywhere.
- Prevent SQL injection via ORM parameterized queries.
- Use environment variables for DATABASE_URL — never hardcode connection strings.
- Apply Prisma select to limit returned fields (especially exclude password).
- Use cascading deletes carefully — document cascade behavior in schema.
- Validate all user-provided IDs before database queries (prevent IDOR).

==============================
FILE UPLOAD SECURITY
==============================

- Validate file MIME type server-side (only accept image/*).
- Enforce maximum file size limit (e.g., 5MB for card images).
- Generate unique filenames — never use user-provided filenames directly.
- Store uploads outside of the application directory.
- In production, use external storage (S3/Cloudinary) — never serve uploads from app server.

==============================
CORS & HTTP HEADERS
==============================

- Configure CORS with explicit allowed origins per environment:
  Development: http://localhost:3000 (web), http://localhost:8081 (mobile)
  Production: specific domain only
- Do NOT use wildcard (*) origins in production.
- Use Helmet middleware for secure HTTP headers.
- Set appropriate Content-Security-Policy headers.
- Enable rate limiting on authentication endpoints to prevent brute force.

==============================
RATE LIMITING
==============================

- Apply rate limiting on sensitive endpoints:
  /auth/login — max 5 attempts per minute per IP
  /auth/register — max 3 attempts per minute per IP
  /upload/* — max 10 uploads per minute per user
- Use Redis (Upstash) for distributed rate limit state in production.
- Return 429 Too Many Requests when limit is exceeded.

==============================
ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
==============================

Required environment variables (never hardcode these):
- DATABASE_URL — PostgreSQL connection string
- JWT_ACCESS_SECRET — access token signing key
- JWT_REFRESH_SECRET — refresh token signing key
- JWT_ACCESS_EXPIRATION — access token TTL
- JWT_REFRESH_EXPIRATION — refresh token TTL
- REDIS_URL — Redis connection (production)
- CORS_ORIGIN — allowed frontend origins
- NODE_ENV — environment identifier

- Provide .env.example with all required keys (no values).
- Never commit .env files to version control.

==============================
LOGGING
==============================

- Do NOT log sensitive data (passwords, tokens, full request bodies with sensitive fields).
- Log authentication failures with IP address and timestamp.
- Log authorization failures with user ID and attempted resource.
- Log errors with enough context to debug but without exposing secrets.
- Use structured logging format for production (JSON).

==============================
FRONTEND SECURITY
==============================

- Store access token in memory (Zustand) — not in localStorage.
- Use httpOnly cookies for refresh tokens when possible.
- Implement automatic token refresh via Axios interceptors.
- Clear all auth state on logout.
- Never expose API keys or secrets in frontend code.
- Sanitize user-generated content before rendering (XSS prevention).
